WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.520
Imagine a technology that simultaneously over-surveils and completely ignores the exact same group

00:00:07.520 --> 00:00:13.280
of people. That double-bind is called coded exposure. This matters because law enforcement

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:18.000
heavily relies on facial recognition software to identify criminal suspects.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:23.600
Take the commercial facial analysis systems used to scan diverse populations on the street.

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:28.480
To see how accurate these tools really are, researchers tested major algorithms

00:00:28.560 --> 00:00:32.480
by mapping their performance across four intersectional demographic groups.

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:38.080
For lighter-skinned men, the systems were virtually flawless. Their error rate was less than 1%.

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:43.360
But when the exact same algorithms processed images of darker-skinned women,

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:50.640
the error rate drastically spiked to 34.7%. This massive gap reveals the paradox of coded

00:00:50.640 --> 00:00:55.680
exposure. The demographic group most heavily targeted by police surveillance networks

00:00:55.680 --> 00:00:59.920
is the exact same group these algorithms are the worst at identifying.

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:04.720
When a system can't accurately distinguish faces within a heavily policed community,

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:09.840
it inevitably generates confident, erroneous matches that turn innocent individuals into

00:01:09.840 --> 00:01:15.600
targets. So today, being invisible to a facial recognition algorithm doesn't protect you from

00:01:15.600 --> 00:01:31.520
surveillance. It actively increases your risk of being falsely accused by it.
